\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The analytical theory developed so far is sufficient to answer many of our
 counterfactual questions when parameter values are known.
 However, to take the model to the data, I require additional structure
 to exploit the firm, product, location, and year variation available for
 estimation.
 In this section, I extend the model to allow firms to innovate in many
 locations and across many products.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We again do not model any dynamic interdependence in the innovation process,
 but we do observe multiple years of data for each firm.
 We treat each year of data as an observation of the firm in steady state,
 and hence is equivalent to treating each firm-year as a separate 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 index.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 These additional dimensions will allow us to leverage multiple kinds of
 within-firm variation in innovation and production outcomes to identify
 model parameters.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The empirical model will introduce several forms of structural residuals:
 demand shocks, innovation shocks, and cost shocks.
 Demand shocks allow the model to match either observed input demand shares
 across suppliers or final demand shares across OEMs.
 Innovation shocks allow the model to replicate observed patent outcomes
 across firms, parts, and locations.
 And cost shocks allow the model to replicate how OEMs allocate R&D across
 inputs.
 Estimation utilizes moment conditions based on all three types of residuals
 and their associated instruments.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of the economic environment is summarized in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: Model Timing"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and consists of three stages: entry, contracting, and R&D.
 Only the final stage is modeled and estimated.
 Describing the earlier stages clarifies what endogenous choices the estimation
 ultimately conditions on.
 In the entry stage, suppliers and OEMs decide whether to operate and in
 which countries to locate production and R&D facilities, paying any necessary
 fixed costs.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXX
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Models of this margin of firm behavior include X and X.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the empirical implementation, I condition on the observed set of active
 firms and locations.
 I do not model endogenous entry or relocation in response to policy or
 counterfactual shocks.
 In the contracting stage, OEMs and suppliers form firm-to-firm relationships,
 and OEMs offer input contracts specifying input purchases.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXX
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Models of this margin of firm behavior include X and X.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Here, I take the observed supply-chain network as given and do not allow
 the discrete network of firm-to-firm connections to change.
 In the R&D stage, firms choose R&D expenditures, and OEMs set prices for
 final consumers.
 All the endogenous decisions analyzed in the structural estimation occur
 in this stage.
 
\end_layout

