\begin_layout Subsection
Upstream Firms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section characterizes the supplier's R&D problem and derives a mapping
 from observables, quantities, costs, and geography, to innovation and pricing
 decisions that can be taken to the data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\equiv\left(i,p,t\right)$
\end_inset

 index the tuple of the supplier 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, product 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 I occasionally refer to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

firm
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, as it is the unit which optimizes R&D.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m\equiv\left(p,j,k,t\right)$
\end_inset

 index a market, where in each year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 demand an input 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 at the location 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 where it operates an assembly plant.
 Following the micro foundation from Section X, the demand a supplier 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 faces in a market 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{f,m}=x_{m}\frac{\xi_{f,m}p_{f,m}^{-\theta}}{P_{m}^{-\theta}},\label{eq: Market Demand}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the total input demand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{f.m}$
\end_inset

 is a supplier-specific demand shifter, and
\begin_inset Formula $P_{m}^{-\theta}=\sum_{f\in F\left(m\right)}p_{f',m}^{-\theta}\xi_{f',m}$
\end_inset

 is the input price index
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
for inputs where the summand is over the set of firms active in a market
 
\begin_inset Formula $F(m)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{f.m}$
\end_inset

 summarizes supplier–specific idiosyncratic demand shocks, and finally 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{f,m}$
\end_inset

 is each suppliers' price
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{f,p,j,k}$
\end_inset

 represent the mean of the Frechet draws for supplier 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in market 
\begin_inset Formula $p,j,k$
\end_inset

.
 Again, each infinitesimal unit of production 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi\in\left[0,x_{p,j,k}\right]$
\end_inset

 has an idiosyncratic preference for the input supplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{f,m}\left(\chi\right)\sim\text{Frechet}\left(\xi_{f,m},\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For the price index, the summand is over 
\begin_inset Formula $F(m)$
\end_inset

, the set of firms active in a market.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{f,m}$
\end_inset

 are determined by the OEM's optimal contracting problem, and both 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{m}$
\end_inset

 are equilibrium objects that are taken as given when choosing R&D.
 In equilibrium, cost reductions increase quantities through the demand
 elasticity 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, and they additionally alter input demand through OEM competition in final
 markets and rivals' pricing in input markets.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The effect of cost reductions on rival's pricing is ambiguous and discussed
 in equation X.
 There is a tradeoff between the expansion in input demand and the market
 stealing effects.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, a firm 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 chooses an R&D portfolio across countries 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and buyers 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 that, maximizes their profits across markets (or equivalently minimizes
 their cost of delivering on their input contract): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\left\{ I_{f,c},I_{f,j,c}\right\} _{j,c}}\sum_{\left\{ m|t_{m}=t\right\} }q_{f,m}\left(p_{f.m}-\frac{c_{f,m}}{I_{f}^{\rho}I_{f,j_{m}}^{\rho}}\right)-\sum_{c}r_{c}^{\zeta}\left(I_{f,c}+\sum_{j}I_{f,j,c}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{f,m}$
\end_inset

 denotes baseline production cost and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{c}^{\zeta}$
\end_inset

 denotes the unit cost of R&D.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This profit expression follows from the demand system and markup micro-foundatio
n in Section X.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Innovation has two components.
 Generic R&D, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{f}$
\end_inset

 lowers costs for all buyers.
 Specialized R&D, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 lowers costs only for buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Generic innovation scales with total output, while specialized innovation
 varies with output of particular buyers.
 The relative importance of these two components depends on the distribution
 of sales across buyers and productivity along either margin.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To account for the fact that suppliers are multinational innovators, total
 R&D levels are a CES aggregate of country-level R&D expenditure:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{f}=\left(\sum_{c}\left[I_{f,c}\zeta_{f,c}\right]^{\varsigma}\right)^{1/\varsigma}\text{ and I_{f,j}=\left(\sum_{c}\left[I_{f,j}\zeta_{f,j,c}\right]^{\zeta}\right)^{1/\varsigma}}.
\]

\end_inset

The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma$
\end_inset

 governs the substitutability of R&D across locations.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the limiting case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma=1$
\end_inset

, innovation is only conducted at the location with the highest cost-adjusted
 R&D productivity.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{f,j,c}$
\end_inset

 capture heterogeneity in R&D productivity of locations according to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\zeta_{f,c}=\varepsilon_{f,c}K_{p_{f},c}^{\omega}d_{f,c}^{\tau_{f}}\text{ and }\zeta_{f,j,c}=\varepsilon_{f,j,c}K_{p_{f},c}^{\omega}d_{f,j,c}^{\tau_{fj}}.\label{eq: R&D Productivity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Productivity depends on the local knowledge stock 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{p_{f},c}$
\end_inset

, proximity to the supplier's own manufacturing 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 and proximity to buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

's manufacturing 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{f,j,c}$
\end_inset

, along with unobserved residual productivity components 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{f,j,c}$
\end_inset

.
 The elasticities 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{f}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $,\tau_{fj}$
\end_inset

 govern how R&D productivity responds to local conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Discussion of Assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The empirical specification relies on three substantive assumptions.
 First, that prices are fixed from the contracting stage when choosing R&D.
 OEMs anticipate suppliers' R&D response when offering input contracts,
 and equilibrium prices incorporate the supplier's optimal innovation subject
 to participation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, R&D decisions are independent across parts and years.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The model timing does allow across-product or across-time interactions at
 the extensive margin: e.g.
 the fixed cost of opening an R&D facility can be shared across parts.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Innovation for one part does not affect payoffs from other parts, and each
 firm-part-year observation is treated as a steady state.
 In Appendix Section X, I examine the empirical relevance of cross-product
 innovation by looking at correlation in innovation outcomes within a firm.
 And, in Proposition X, I explain how the static R&D problem is isomorphic
 to a model in which firms choose the steady-state level of an accumulated
 R&D stock.
 The estimation therefore captures long-run innovation responses rather
 than transitional dynamics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, production, R&D locations, and firm-to-firm connections are fixed
 at this stage.
 Firms choose these margins in the entry and network formation stages, anticipat
ing the payoffs characterized in the final stage.
 In the empirical implementation, I condition on the observed geography
 of firms and network of linkages.
 However, if these choices are made conditional on the unobserved demand
 and innovation shocks at the final stage, then there is scope for selection
 bias in the estimation.
 I later develop instruments to address these concerns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Characterizing the R&D Allocation for Upstream Firm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To characterize how R&D is allocated, it is useful to define two productivity
 indices that summarize the effective cost of raising generic and buyer-specific
 innovation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\zeta}_{f}=\left(\sum_{c}\left[\zeta_{f}r_{c}^{-\zeta}\right]^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}\right)^{\frac{1-\varsigma}{\varsigma}}\text{ and }\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}=\left(\sum_{c}\left[\zeta_{f,j,c}r_{c}^{-\zeta}\right]^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}\right)^{\frac{1-\varsigma}{\varsigma}}.\label{eq: R&D Productivity Shifters}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These objects aggregate cross-country productivity differences into a single
 sufficient statistic for each innovation type.
 They incorporate both technological advantages and R&D costs, and account
 for the optimal allocation of R&D across countries implied by the CES structure.
 A higher value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a lower effective marginal cost of raising the relevant
 R&D component.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, define buyer-level aggregates over markets: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{q}_{f,j}=\sum_{m}\mathbb{1}\left\{ j_{m}=j\right\} q_{f,m}\text{ and }\bar{c}_{f,j}=\sum_{m}\mathbb{1}\left\{ j_{m}=j\right\} \frac{q_{f,m}}{\bar{q}_{f,j}}c_{f,m}/
\]

\end_inset

The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 denotes total sales from supplier 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 across all plants, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding quantity-weighted average cost of supplying buyer
 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

's plants.
 These aggregates summarize the scale and cost conditions relevant for specializ
ing R&D towards each buyer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, I turn to characterizing the firm's optimal allocation of R&D.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop: Suppliers R&D Allocation"

\end_inset

Suppliers allocate their R&D as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
a relative allocation across generic and specialized R&D that satisfies
\shape default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{I_{f}}{\bar{\zeta}_{f}}=\sum_{j}\frac{I_{f,j}}{\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
a relative allocation across specialized R&D recipients that satisfies
\shape default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{I_{f,j}}{\sum I_{f,j}}=\frac{\left(\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}\bar{q}_{f,j}\bar{c}_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\rho}}}{\sum_{j}\left(\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}\bar{q}_{f,j}\bar{c}_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\rho}}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
and a relative allocation across countries that satisfies
\shape default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{I_{f,c}}{\sum_{c'}I_{f,c'}}=\frac{\left(\zeta_{f,c}/r_{c}\right)^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}}{\sum_{c'}\left(\zeta_{f,c'}/r_{c}\right)^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}}\text{ and }\frac{I_{f,j,c}}{\sum_{c'}I_{f,j,c}}=\frac{\left(\zeta_{f,j,c}/r_{c}\right)^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}}{\sum_{c'}\left(\zeta_{f,j,c'}/r_{c'}\right)^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This characterization highlights three economic forces.
 First, the division between generic and specialized R&D reflects their
 relative productivity and returns.
 When generic R&D is highly productive (high 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f}$
\end_inset

), suppliers tilt investment towards cost reductions that benefits all buyers.
 When buyer-specific productivity is high, specialized R&D becomes more
 attractive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, specialized R&D is allocated towards buyers for which suppliers
 are productive 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

, have high quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

, and have high cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

.
 Higher quantities increase the scale over which cost-reducing innovations
 apply, and higher cost increase the marginal benefit of innovation.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In equilibrium, higher costs will also reduce the quantities that suppliers
 receive.
 Both through competition in input markets, and reduced input purchase from
 downstream firms.
 The equilibrium implications of cost shocks should therefore not be interpreted
 as shocks that necessarily increase innovation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When the elasticity 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 increases, diminishing returns become weaker and R&D is spread more evenly
 across buyers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, the cross-country allocation of R&D reflects a standard CES tradeoff
 between productivity and cost.
 R&D flows to locations where productivity is high relative to costs.
 And as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, expenditure concentrates in the single most productive location.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This theory suggests why directly interpreting reduced-form coefficients
 from innovation outcomes as causal coefficients, even when using instruments,
 is problematic.
 As R&D will endogenously be allocated to the locations where it is most
 productive.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To make sense of this result, the differences in R&D productivity introduced
 in 
