caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 suggest that the marginal cost of raising generic innovation, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{f,p}$
\end_inset

, differs from that of raising specialized innovation, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{f,j,p}$
\end_inset

.
 It is easier to raise generic R&D if firms are located closer to their
 own plants, and likewise easier to raise specialized R&D if firms are located
 closer to their customers plants.
 The overall productivity of each type of R&D spending is by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: R&D Productivity Shifters"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which as discussed is a sort of productivity index constructed from difference
s in productivity cross countries and the corresponding optimal across-country
 R&D distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Now, when looking across buyers within specialized R&D, firms are more likely
 to allocate R&D to buyers for which they are productive 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

, which have high quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

, and which have high cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

.
 Where again, a supplier high high R&D productivity for a buyer if it is
 proximate to it.
 As for the role of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is high and innovations are easy to accomplish, R&D portfolios are therefore
 spread more evenly across buyers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finally, when we consider the across-country distribution of R&D, these
 arise from either productivity differences or cost differences.
 Where as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, R&D becomes increasingly concentrated in the location where it is most
 productivity.
 This theory also sheds light for why directly interpreting reduced-form
 coefficients on the R&D outcomes as causal coefficients is problematic,
 since R&D will endogenously be allocated to the locations where it is most
 productivity.
 So with sufficiently high substitutability, even small productivity difference
 might materialize as large observed effects.
 Taking these results together, we can next turn to characterizing the total
 level of innovation.
 
