\]

\end_inset

Prices reflect four components: markups from optimal contracting, baseline
 production costs, buyer-specific innovation, and generic innovation.
 The buyer-specific component lowers prices more when suppliers sell large
 quantities to a buyer, face high baseline costs for that buyer, or have
 high productivity in specialized R&D towards that buyer.
 The generic component lowers prices for all buyers, and depends on the
 distribution of scale, costs, and R&D productivity across all buyers.
 Several implications follow.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, not just pure scale, but the distribution of scale across buyers
 shapes innovation.
 Larger total sales raises the marginal benefit of cost reductions, increasing
 both generic and specialized R&D.
 But when the output is concentrated in a single buyer, marginal returns
 to additional specialized R&D are diminished.
 This alters the elasticity of innovation with respect to scale.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, innovation dampens cost pass-through.
 If we assume there is only one market with a single buyer, and differentiate
 prices with respect to baseline costs, we have
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{f,m}=c_{f,m}\left(\bar{q}_{f,j_{m}}\bar{c}_{f,j_{m}}\right)^{\frac{-\rho}{1+\rho}}\underbrace{\left(\sum_{j}\left(\bar{q}_{f,j}\bar{c}_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\rho}}\right)^{\frac{-\rho}{1+2\rho}}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{f,m}=c_{f,m}\left(\bar{q}_{f,j_{m}}\bar{c}_{f,j_{m}}\right)^{\frac{-2\rho}{1+2\rho}}
\]

\end_inset

So we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log p_{f,m}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,m}}=\frac{1}{1+2\rho}-\frac{2\rho}{1+2\rho}\frac{d\log q_{f,m}}{d\log p_{f,m}}\frac{d\log p_{f,m}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,m}}
\]

\end_inset

which gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log p_{f,m}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,m}}\left(1+\frac{2\rho}{1+2\rho}\frac{d\log q_{f,m}}{d\log p_{f,m}}\right)=\frac{1}{1+2\rho}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log p_{f,m}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,m}}=\frac{1}{1+2\rho}/\left(1+\frac{2\rho}{1+2\rho}\frac{d\log q_{f,m}}{d\log p_{f,m}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log p_{f,m}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,m}}=\frac{1}{1+2\rho}/\left(1+\frac{2\rho}{1+2\rho}\frac{d\log q_{f,m}}{d\log p_{f,m}}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Cost increases induce additional R&D investment, offsetting the direct effect
 on prices.
 Fixing quantities, pass through is therefore strictly less than one.
 Of course in equilibrium, increased input costs themselves pass through
 to contracted input prices and then to final prices, lowering downstream
 quantities and input demand.
 Lower demand may undo the increased R&D incentive from higher cost.
 And, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently large and downstream market sufficiently elastic, innovation
 may instead amplify cost pass-through.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, the allocation of R&D across countries shapes prices through the
 productivity indices 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

.
 R&D proximity to manufacturing affects prices only through its effect on
 R&D productivity and hence innovation and costs.
 The geography of production therefore influence demand directly through
 baseline costs, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{f,m}$
\end_inset

, and indirectly via an innovation channel.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These relationships summarize the core mechanisms of the upstream model.
 Scale, buyer concentration, and manufacturing proximity jointly determine
 innovation, which in turn shapes prices and market shares.
 The reduced-form analysis that follows isolates these forces empirically,
 providing evidence for their presence.
 And, the structural estimation quantities their magnitude.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reduced-Form Estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The structural model delivers predictions linking scale, network structure,
 and manufacturing proximity to innovation and market outcomes.
 Before turning to the full structural estimation, this section evaluates
 those predictions in reduced form, clarifies the key identification challenges,
 and develops a corresponding set of instruments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Threats to Identification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The novel parameters of interest are 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{f}\text{ and }\tau_{fj}$
\end_inset

, which govern the elasticity of R&D productivity with respect to manufacturing
 proximity.
 Quantifying these is crucial to understanding the innovation benefits from
 reshoring policy.
 In general, I will assume the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{E}\left[d_{f,c}\varepsilon_{f,c}\right]\neq0.\label{eq: Endogeneity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is, manufacturing proximity may be endogenous and correlated with unobserve
d determinants of R&D productivity.
 Firms may co-locate R&D and production in locations that have favorable
 institution environments, skilled labor pools, or targeted industrial policy.
 For instance, Bosch (the world's largest auto parts suppliers) both manufacture
s and innovates in Germany, its headquarter country.
 If we observe that Bosch innovates a lot in Germany, should we interpret
 the observed correlation between R&D outcomes and the presence of local
 manufacturing as evidence of a causal effect? Likely not.
 More reasonably, there is some unaccounted for factor that drives this
 relationship.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To navigate this identification concern, the empirical strategy utilizes
 two assumptions.
 First, a conditional independence assumption, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{E}\left[d_{f,c}\varepsilon_{f,c}|\text{Supplier-Location-Year and Part-Location-Year Fixed Effects}\right]=0.\label{eq: Conditional Independence}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Identification comes from across product variation in manufacturing proximity
 within firm-location, where conditioning on high-dimensional fixed effects
 controls for unobserved local features like subsidies, demand conditions,
 or access to headquarter services.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even with this assumption, reasonable explanations exist for endogeneity
 concerns that might persist at the firm-country-part level.
 For example, there has been considerable industrial policy efforts in subsidizi
ng specifically battery production and innovation.
 If they are targeted to specific firms, and hence not absorbed by a part-locati
on fixed effect, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Conditional Independence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 would not be satisfied.
 Therefore, I employ a set of instruments that can predict 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 - the presence of manufacturing - but are plausibly orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 - the unobserved component of R&D productivity.
 These instruments are based on trade policy variation across countries
 and parts and are discussed in detail below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, I take steps to motivate a reduced-form specification, starting with
 assumptions on the measurements of model objects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
