\begin_layout Definition
The buyer concentration index, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\text{BCI}}_{f}$
\end_inset

, is defined as the sum of production shares of a given supplier across
 buyers, each raised to the power 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{BCI}_{f}\left(\alpha\right)=\sum_{j}\left(\frac{\bar{q}_{f,j}}{\sum_{j'}\bar{q}_{f,j'}}\right)^{\alpha}.\label{eq: BCI Definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=2$
\end_inset

, coincides with the Herfindahl–Hirschman index applied to a supplier's
 sales across buyers.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>1$
\end_inset

, the index increases as sales become more concentrated.
 As
\begin_inset Formula $\text{BCI}_{f}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, the supplier sells to many buyers; as 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{BCI}_{f}\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, the sales converge on a single buyer.
 Under simplifying assumptions, the we will first show how 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{BCI}_{f}$
\end_inset

 interacts with measures of scale as well as proximity to shape innovation
 outcomes.
 
\end_layout

