\begin_layout Standard
This expression captures three effects.
 First, larger scale increases innovation as productivity improvements apply
 to more units, raising the marginal return to R&D.
 Second, the elasticity of innovation with respect to scale declines as
 sales become more concentrated.
 Quantity growth that comes from one buyer is subject to diminishing marginal
 returns, while quantity growth that comes from new buyers allows for additional
 directions of specialized R&D where marginal returns are high.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the data, this might reflect the fact that buyers differentiate their
 products in dimensions other than price.
 Such that when a supplier works with a new buyer, they are expected to
 deliver innovations that differentiate the resulting final product of the
 buyer from its competitions.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Third, holding scale fixed, greater concentration increases R&D spending
 in a single buyer and subject to the parameter restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\rho/\left(1+\rho\right)>1$
\end_inset

, this increased observed patenting despite the face that the marginal returns
 to innovation fall.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For some intuition behind this result, note that the assumptions put us
 in the case where firms differ only in the scale of their production and
 the number of homogenous buyers they have.
 Naturally, the larger the scale of production, the more firms will innovation
 due to greater profit incentives - cost savings are made on a larger number
 of units.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 becomes larger this elasticity falls - easier innovations make changes
 in incentives weaker at inducing change in R&D.
 Now, as for the negative coefficient on the interaction, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{BCI}_{f}$
\end_inset

 becomes larger, more innovation is targeted towards one buyer.
 Given diminishing returns to innovation at the buyer-level, we see a weaker
 effect of quantity increases when they are coming from few buyers.
 Put differently, if quantity growth is coming from the number of buyers,
 firms see additional innovation since they can invest in new directions
 of specialized R&D.
 Finally, there is a positive effect of the level of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{BCI}_{f}$
\end_inset

 that comes from that fact that with only one buyer, the specialized component
 of R&D is all funneled into one buyer.
 The sign of this last result depends on the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\rho/\left(1+\rho\right)>1$
\end_inset

 - which is borne out in the estimation of Section X.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXXThis is quintessential benefit of competition.
 More innovation.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now turning to predictions for the geography of innovation, Assumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assu: Observability of Innovation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 implies that the across-country distribution of patents reflects the geographic
 allocation of R&D spending and R&D productivity.
 In the model, patents can shift across locations for two reasons.
 First, firms may reallocate generic R&D towards locations where generic
 R&D is more productive (e.g.
 closer to own manufacturing).
 Second, they may reallocate specialized R&D towards locations where specialized
 R&D is more productive (e.g.
 closer to a buyer's manufacturing).
 Which firm dominates depends on the relative importance of generic versus
 specialized R&D in the firm's R&D portfolio.
 Under the simplifying assumption of Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Reduced Form Log Patents"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the ratio of the two R&D types is precisely characterized by the buyer
 concentration index, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{BCI}_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 
