\begin_layout Standard
This expression highlights two components.
 The first term is a location share for generic R&D, which depends on the
 relative productivity and cost of conducting generic R&D cross countries.
 The second term captures a complementary share, but for specialized R&D.
 It, however, is scaled by the importance of specialized innovation in the
 firm's R&D portfolio.
 Under the maintained assumptions, buyer concentration summarizes specialized
 R&Ds relevance for patenting: as concentration rises, buyer-specific innovation
 becomes more important and the specialized location share receives greater
 weight.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result implies sharp comparative statics.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{BCI}_{f}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, sales are dispersed, specialized R&D is diluted across buyers, and the
 observed geography of patents is increasingly governed by generic R&D productiv
ity.
 In this case patenting across countries should co-vary primarily with proximity
 to the supplier's own manufacturing.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{BCI}_{f}\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, sales concentrate, and differences in specialized research productivity
 increasingly shape the geography of patents.
 In this case, patenting across countries should covary more strongly with
 proximity to buyers' manufacturing.
