\begin_layout Subsubsection
Endogeneity and Instruments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reduced-form specification relies on within-group variation and a rich
 set of controls, but proximity and quantity may remain endogenous to unobserved
 innovation determinants.
 In the model, the relevant threat is correlation between proximity and
 the innovation productivity residual.
 In addition, quantity is jointly determined with R&D: firms with high innovatio
n productivity have lower costs and therefore large quantities, introducing
 a simultaneity problem in regressions that use scale to infer returns to
 innovation.
 I therefore introduce instruments for manufacturing proximity and production
 scale.
 We use the reduced-form setting as an opportunity to test the instruments,
 but ultimately their use in the structural GMM estimation identifies model
 parameters.
 In addition, we consider a stronger version of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Conditional Independence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, where we use more granular variation at the firm-city-part-year level,
 allowing a richer set of controls.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Finer granularity: variation from across cities within countries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conditional independence assumption in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Conditional Independence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 would be violated by endogeneity persisting at the firm-country-part level.
 One example is targeted, firm-specific support for a particular technology,
 such as subsidies to battery production and battery R&D, that varies within
 a firm-country across parts.
 One approach to address this concern, is to re-estimate the model at a
 finer geographic granularity, constructing firm-city-part-year observation.
 This allows me to use firm-country-part-year fixed effect and identify
 the proximity effect using only the variation across cities within that
 group.
 Column 5 implements this design; the same qualitative pattern of results
 continues to hold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Location instruments: tariffs and predicted plant location.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To instrument for the geography of production and demand, I use variation
 in trade policy across parts and countries, similar in spirit to the event
 study in Section X.
 The core idea us that part-specific tariff rates levied by countries shift
 the incentives to locate manufacturing and to serve markets, generating
 variation in the proximity measures, while ideally being orthogonal to
 unobserved local R&D productivity (condition on high-dimensional fixed
 effects).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get some intuition for the instrument, consider a supplier that makes
 Engines and Transmissions, operates plants in Mexico and the US, and sells
 its output to the US.
 Intuitively, if the US has a high tariff rate on Engines and a low tariff
 rate on Transmissions, the supplier might locate Engine manufacturing in
 the US to avoid import taxes and Transmission manufacturing in Mexico to
 benefit from lower wages.
 The exclusion restriction here being that tariffs are orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 - the unobserved component of local R&D productivity in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Endogeneity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, to get an instrument that can also help predict where demand
 is, we interact the part tariff with the tariff rate on assembled cars.
 Where similarly, a higher tariff rate on assembled cars makes production
 in a country more likely.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Operationally, I estimate a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

zero-stage
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 regression for the probability that a given supplier 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 has (or sells to) a plant producing (or purchasing) part 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in country 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\left\{ \text{Supplier, Buyer}\right\} $
\end_inset

 denote whether the outcome concerns a supplier production plant or a downstream
 assembly plant.
 I estimate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\text{X Plant}_{i,c,p,t}\right)^{-1}=1+\exp\left(-\left(\beta_{1}^{X}\text{Part Tariff}_{p,c,t}+\beta_{2}^{X}\text{Part Tariff}_{p,c,t}\times\text{Assembly Tariff}_{c,t}+\delta_{i,c,t}^{X}+\varepsilon_{i,c,p,t}\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{i,c,t}^{X}$
\end_inset

 ensures the variation comes from across parts within firm-country.
 The results from this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

zero-stage
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 regression are in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: Plant Zero Stage"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Conditional on 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{i,c,t}^{\text{X}}$
\end_inset

 , higher tariff rates make a supplier more likely to both operate a plant
 in and sell to a particular country-part.
 But when said country also has a high tariff rate on assembled cars, the
 Supplier plant effect of tariffs becomes stronger, while the Buyer plant
 effect becomes weaker.
 For intuition, a higher tariff on final goods makes domestic production
 more likely, raising the expected local demand for all parts.
 This makes the effects of part-specific tariffs for predicting demand weaker
 since demand is already saturated by the final good tariff.
 
