\begin_layout Standard
A remaining concern is that tariffs are not randomly assigned: they may
 respond to existing manufacturing.
 This does not invalidate the instrument unless tariffs also responding
 directly, or indirectly, to unobserved local innovation productivity in
 the relevant part, conditional on the fixed effects structure.
 For instance, one concern is that firms observed good R&D shocks for a
 particular location, located manufacturing and R&D in that location, and
 then lobbied for a higher tariff rate to protect their investment.
 In this case if policy was responding to the average level of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 across firms, then the part-country-year fixed effect in the second-stage
 would control for this possibility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason we are able to include a part-country-year fixed effect, despite
 the fact that tariffs rates are administered at this level, is that the
 constructed instrument 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: Geography IV Equation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 does vary across firms within part-country-year.
 This is due both to the baseline probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{i,c,t}^{X}$
\end_inset

, and due to the set of countries that are summed over in the instrument
 constriction.
 So one loose interpretation of the instrument is a sort of shift-share
 design where the shifts are tariff shocks and the shares are exposures
 to the countries in which those shocks are occurring.
 This raises another concern that what the instrument is capturing is not
 the effect of tariff shocks themselves, but the baseline exposure to tariff
