noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, would make a firm's predicted proximity more dependent on tariff shocks
 in that location.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 I assume, consistent with the exclusion restriction, that part tariffs
 are randomly assigned within firm-country-year.
 And thus, I can employ randomization inference, whereby I randomly sample
 from the distribution of tariff shocks within a firm-country-year to determine
 the baseline exposure to that country's tariffs, and recenter the instrument
 accordingly.
 The reduced-form results from both of these robustness checks are in the
 Appendix Section X, and the recentered instrument is used for the structural
 estimation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Demand instruments: export demand shocks to downstream buyers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To instrument for supplier scale, and the distribution of supplier sales
 across buyers, I construct a shift-share demand instrument based on downstream
 export demand shocks.
 The key time-series variation is demand for specific vehicle models in
 export markets.
 I predict changes in model-level demand using baseline export shares in
 an initial period and destination-market demand shifters (e.g.
 GDP per capita changes), producing predicted model demand growth that is
 plausibly exogenous to supplier innovation shocks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, consider a car model 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 For every model, we observe the exports in each year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 from an origin country 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 to a destination country 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{5}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 denote the first 5 years of observation for model 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 We define the baseline bilateral export share for model 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{\ensuremath{\lambda}}_{\omega.k,c}=\frac{\sum_{t\in T^{5}\left(\omega\right)}\text{Exports}_{\omega,t,k,c}}{\sum_{t\in T^{5}\left(\omega\right)}\sum_{c'}\text{Exports}_{\omega,t,k,c'}}.
\]

\end_inset

We predict future exports in a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

zero-stage
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 regression using a shift-share design with shares given by baseline export
 shares and shifts given by GDP per-capita in destination market:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{\omega,k,t}=\beta\sum_{c\neq k}\text{\ensuremath{\lambda}}_{\omega.k,c}\times GDP_{c,t}^{pc}+\delta_{\omega,k}+\varepsilon_{\omega,k,t}
\]

\end_inset

To map buyer demand shocks to suppliers, we use observed buyer-supplier
 linkages at the part level.
 A supplier's predicted quantity shock is the weighted sum of predicted
 demand shocks for the models and buyers it serves.
 In addition to shifting total quantities, this also shifts the distribution
 of sales across buyers - either increasing or decreasing buyer concentration.
 
\end_layout

