\begin_layout Subsubsection
Additional Evidence for Specialized Innovation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key mechanism in the model is notion of specialized R&D: suppliers can
 direct innovation to particular buyers.
 This mechanism has not only distributional consequences for which buyers
 face lower prices inputs, but also aggregate implications.
 When output expands through the extensive margin, suppliers obtain a new
 direction in which to invest specialized R&D, implying that innovation
 can rise by more than would be predicted by scale effects alone.
 The reduced-form evidence in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: Reduced Form Estimation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 provides indirect evidence for this mechanism through the role of the buyer-con
centration index.
 To provide more direct evidence on the direction in innovation, I use patent
 citation links between suppliers and buyers.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fadeev2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 discusses how citation data may not reflect knowledge spillovers, but rather
 direction knowledge transfers between firms.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assu: Observability of Directed"

\end_inset

