\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Our model makes predictions on R&D allocations at the firm-part-country
 level.
 While accessing data on R&D allocations at this level of granularity is
 hard to imagine, data on patents - which are publicly available - is available.
 And, mapping patents to locations, firms, and parts is the subject of Section
 X.
 Note, patents should be viewed as an outcome of the R&D process rather
 than an input, hence we map them to model innovations rather than R&D inputs
 (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{f}^{\rho}$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{f}$
\end_inset

).
 We will proceed with two sets of assumptions on what patents measure.
 The first will allow us to interpret model parameters in terms of the causal
 effect on patents themselves, and the second will allow us to interpret
 parameters in terms of the causal effect on costs or buyers willingness
 to pay.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The allocation of R&D is determined by four sufficient statistics: R&D productiv
ity indices 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bar{\zeta}_{f},\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}\}$
\end_inset

, quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

, and costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \bar{c}_{f,j},r_{c}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 I observe quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{q}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

, but not 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bar{\zeta}_{f},\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}\}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \bar{c}_{f,j},r_{c}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Under Assumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assu: Observability of Innovation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, patent data disciplines the R&D productivity indices.
 As for costs, I assume that up to a set of parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta\equiv\left\{ \vartheta_{w},\vartheta_{d},\vartheta_{r}\right\} $
\end_inset

, costs can be constructed from country-level observables and data on the
 plant locations of firms with the following measurement assumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assu: Observability of Costs"

\end_inset

Observability of Costs.
 The cost that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 faces when supplying market 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 can be measured as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{f,m}=\sum_{c}\left(\frac{\text{Wage}_{c}}{\text{TFP}_{c}}\right)^{\vartheta_{w}}\left(\text{Distance}_{c.m}\right)^{\vartheta_{d}}\mathbb{1}\left\{ c=\arg\min_{c\in\boldsymbol{C}\left(f\right)}\text{Distance}_{c.m}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{C}\left(f\right)$
\end_inset

 is the set of plants operated by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 And, the costs of R&D in country 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 can be measured as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{c}=\left(\frac{\text{Wage}_{c}}{\text{TFP}_{c}\times\text{Human Capital Index}_{c}}\right)^{\vartheta_{r}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that baseline production costs, before R&D is applied, depend
 on productivity-adjusted wages at a plant's location and the distance between
 a plant and a buyer.
 And, to determine where production originates from, we assume that suppliers
 use the plant geographically closest to a buyer as the source of inputs.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This leads to the possibility that firms do not actually use the cheapest
 plant when selling to a buyer.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta_{w}>>\vartheta_{d}$
\end_inset

, then the cheapest plant would always be that with the lowest wage regardless
 of the buyer's distance.
 Then, under least-cost sourcing, there would be no reason for suppliers
 to operate multiple plants and many of the plants we observe in the data
 would serve no purpose.
 So we impose that the closest observed plant to a destination must be used
 as a tractable proxy.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The export platforms literature typically assumes that there is some substituta
bility across plants such that the cost of servicing a destination depends
 on some cost index derived from the whole set of plants operated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tintelnot2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 If I observed sourcing decisions directly it would provide some guidance
 on how better to construct 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{f,j,k}$
\end_inset

.
 Since I do not, I make this measurement assumption in place.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Dimensionality and inversion of innovation residuals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model thus far allowed R&D productivity shocks that are specific to
 given buyers: 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{f,j,c}$
\end_inset

 - which has dimensionality 
\begin_inset Formula $F\times J\times C$
\end_inset

 (suppliers 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 buyers 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 countries).
 To start, I will make use only of patent data to discipline the R&D side
 of the model - and such data is only available at the level of 
\begin_inset Formula $F\times C$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, I assume away any residuals that are specific to given buyers.
 In an extension, we consider using citation data under Assumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assu: Observability of Directed"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to allow for buyer-specific residuals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assu: Dimensionality"

\end_inset

Dimensionality.
 The residual component of R&D productivity if common across buyers within
 a firm-country: 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{f,c}=\varepsilon_{f,j,c}\forall j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This assumption reduces the number of unobservable R&D shocks to match the
 number of firm-country patent equations under Assumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assu: Observability of Innovation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 This will generally allow us to invert the model for a unique set of R&D
 residuals consistent with the observed patent distribution.
 .
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\lambda_{f,c}\zeta_{f,c}\right)^{\frac{\rho}{1-\varsigma}}=\text{Patents}_{f,p}^{-1}I_{f}^{\rho}\left(\left(\frac{\left(1/d_{f,c}^{\tau_{f}}\right)^{\frac{1}{1-\varsigma}}}{\left(\bar{\zeta}_{f}\right)^{\frac{1}{1-\varsigma}}}\right)^{\rho}+\sum_{j}\left(\frac{\left(\bar{c}_{f,j}\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}q_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\rho}}}{\sum\left(\bar{c}_{f,j}\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}q_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\rho}}}\frac{\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}}{\bar{\zeta}_{f}}\frac{\left(1/d_{f,j,c}^{\tau_{fj}}\right)^{\frac{1}{1-\varsigma}}}{\left(\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1-\varsigma}}}\right)^{\rho}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{f,p}$
\end_inset

 is given by Equation X, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f},\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 are defined in equation X.
 A sufficient condition for the Jacobian of this system to be a P-matrix,
 and hence for the solution to be unique iss 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1+\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}>\frac{\rho\left(1+2\rho\right)\left(\theta-1\right)}{-\rho+\left(1+\rho\right)\left(1-2\rho\left(\theta-1\right)\right)},
\]

\end_inset

where we rely on Gale and Nikaido (1965) conditions for a P-matrix.
 Proof inspired by Tintelnot 2017.
 Other condition is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-2\rho\left(\theta-1\right)\right)>0$
\end_inset

 for interior solution.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Invertibility.
 Under Assumptions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assu: Observability of Innovation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assu: Observability of Costs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assu: Observability of Directed"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and given data 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{X}$
\end_inset

 (to be formalized), a sufficient condition for a unique set of R&D residuals
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Patent Equation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1+\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}>\frac{\rho\left(1+2\rho\right)}{-\rho+\left(1+\rho\right)\left(1-2\rho\right)}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This condition ensures that mapping from location productivity to the implied
 patent distribution is well behaved.
 Intuitively, it limits the degree of complementarity, either by requiring
 sufficiently high substitution across locations or sufficiently low returns
 to R&D.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Demand residuals are more straightforward.
 Given the model-implied prices from Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Supplier R&D Level and Prices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and observed market shares, the demand shifter enter log-linearly in Equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Market Demand"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and can be recovered as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi_{f,m}=\log\text{Market Share}_{f,m}+\theta\log p_{f,m}.
\]

\end_inset

Finally, with a procedure for recovering residuals in hand, I can specify
 moment conditions that identify parameters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
Orthogonality.
 For a set of instruments 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{\boldsymbol{z}_{f,c}},\boldsymbol{\boldsymbol{z}_{f,m}}\}$
\end_inset

 and fixed effects 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, the residuals R&D residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 and demand residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{f,m}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the following moment conditions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[\log\left(\varepsilon_{f,c}\right)\boldsymbol{z}_{f,c}|\mathcal{X}\right]=0,\qquad\mathbb{E}\left[\log\left(\xi_{f,m}\right)\boldsymbol{z}_{f,m}|\mathcal{X}\right]=0.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
for a set of instruments 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{z}_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 and fixed effects 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathds{1}_{x}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Assumption
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[\log\left(\zeta_{f,c,p,t}\right)|z_{f,c,p,t},\left\{ \mathds{1}_{f,c,p}\right\} ,\left\{ \mathds{1}_{p,c,t}\right\} \right]=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Identification (Across-Firm within Market): the residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{f,j,k}$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[\log\left(\xi_{f,m}\right)\boldsymbol{z}_{f,m}|\left\{ \mathds{1}_{x}\right\} \right]=0
\]

\end_inset

for a set of instruments 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{z}_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 and fixed effects 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathds{1}_{x}\right\} .$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The full set of fixed effects and instruments used for each parameter is
 summarized in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: Identification Summary"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These moment conditions mimic the reduced-form identification discussed
 with Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: Reduced Form Estimation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 On the innovation side, identification comes from within-group variation
 to estimate model parameters, particularly across parts within a firm-country-y
ear or across years within a firm-country-part - controlling for other high-dime
nsional fixed effects in either case.
 On the demand side, identification comes from within-market variation across
 suppliers using the model-implied prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: Identification Summary"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 summarizes the instruments and variation used to identify each parameter.
 Both the returns to innovation 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and spillovers 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 are estimated from time-series variation within firm-country-part in quantities
 and local innovation, instrumented using downstream demand shocks.
 The geographic innovation parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{f},\tau_{f,j},\text{ and }\varsigma$
\end_inset

, are estimated from across-part variation in the location of manufacturing
 within firm-country-year, instrumented using variation in trade policy.
 Cost and demand parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\vartheta_{d},\vartheta_{w},\theta\}$
\end_inset

, are estimated from across-firm variation in cost determinants and model-implie
d prices within markets.
 The only parameter we estimate using primarily across-country variation
 in the R&D cost parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta_{r}$
\end_inset

, which exhibits no variation across products or firms.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In determining R&D costs 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{c}$
\end_inset

, there is no variation across parts within a firm.
 It only varies with location, hence precluding any country fixed effects.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Finally, the patent scaling parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is identified from across-firm differences in patenting within markets.
 
\end_layout

