\begin_layout Paragraph
Validating patents as a measure of productivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A final note on why jointly estimating the innovation side of the model
 and the demand side of the model is useful.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Another version of this paper, closer to prior work on estimating the behavior
 of multinational innovators, would estimate something like the effect of
 R&D and its productivity determinants on total factor productivity (see
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "Bilir.Morales2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

A common approach in firm-level work on innovation is to relate R&D inputs
 and determinants to measures of total factor productivity (TFP) (see for
 example 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "Bilir.Morales2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who also studies multinational manufacturing firms).
 While this has the benefit of tying innovation to an outcome with direct
 economic meaning, it requires proprietary R&D and production data sufficiently
 granular to estimate TFP at the firm-country-year level.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To my knowledge, such data only exists for US multinationals - see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bilir.Morales2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Liu2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

Even with such data, estimating parameters that govern geographic determinants
 of innovation would rely on across-firm or across-country variation - which
 as we outline with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Endogeneity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is subject to numerous endogeneity concerns.
 To implement the instrumental variable strategy in this project, one would
 need firm-country-part-year level estimates of TFP .
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
estimating TFP at the granularity needed for this project is challenging.
 In particular, if one wanted to estimate TFP across-countries within a
 firm, they would require output and input data at the same level, as well
 as R&D expenditures across countries.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To my knowledge, such data only exists for US multinationals - see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bilir.Morales2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Liu2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 But, identification in these papers still relies on across-country differences
 within firms, which as we disucss in Section X, are subject to pressing
 endogeneity concerns when estimating paramters like spillover from manufacturin
g to R&D.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this setting, patents are the observable signal of innovation output.
 But patents, unlike TFP, are not mechanically tied to economic value.
 The model provides a way to discipline such a mapping.
 Specifically, the demand system implies that price differences shape market
 outcomes, and prices are pinned down by both production costs and innovation.
 By jointly fitting the patent moments and market share moments, the estimation
 selects parameters such that patent-based innovation measures rationalize
 observed sourcing patterns through the model-implied price.
 The demand this anchors patents in an economically meaningful outcome:
 patents drive variation in purchases by downstream buyers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be more precise, the sole input used for recovering the demand residual
 is the model-generated price, where estimation ensures that the innovations
 that determine price precisely match patent data: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{f,j}\propto p_{f,m}^{-\theta}\text{ and }p_{f,m}=\mu_{f,m}c_{f,m}\underbrace{\left(I_{f}^{-\rho}I_{f,j_{m}}^{-\rho}\right)}_{\text{\text{Patents}}=I_{f}^{\rho\gamma}+\sum_{j}I_{f,j}^{\rho\gamma}}.
\]

\end_inset

Intuitively, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 governs to what extent patents can be interpreted as productivity-improving
 innovations, and thus can shape market outcomes.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
But such an exercise requires proprietary firm level data, granular enough
 to estimate TFP at the firm-country-year level (at least).
 And, an assumption that the estimated TFP reflected the innovations of
 interest.
 Even without that assumption however, TFP does represent a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 economic quantity in ways that patents do not.
 While it is model dependent, TFP is the residual part of firm performance
 that is not explained by other observables, while patents represent an
 idea that is not definitionally tied to any real economic value.
 One way to make our measure of innovation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - in the sense that it corresponds to true innovations that affect how
 these firms perform in their markets - is to use the demand system for
 inputs to see what variation in demand we can explain through variation
 in patented innovations.
 Namely, the sole input used for recovering the demand residual is the model-gen
erated price,where estimation ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{f}^{\rho\gamma}+\sum_{j}I_{f,j_{m}}^{\varrho\gamma}$
\end_inset

 exactly matches patent data.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 scales patents to the level patents are for determining model innovation.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way to externally validate this mapping it to project an independent
 measure of costs onto patents.
 Where, the theory predicts that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\text{Cost}/d\log\text{Patents}\approx1/2\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 I collect model-part repair costs from Kelly Blue Book for vehicle models
 that are matched to the firm-to-firm data.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kelly Blue Book offers repair costs for fairly broad categories, which I
 crosswalk into the parts sold by supplies.
 For example, suppose Bosch supplies Air Conditioning Systems to the Volkswagen
 Golf.
 I match the AC repair costs on Kelly Blue Book to Bosch and regress it
 on Bosch patents in AC systems.
 Note repair costs are available only for models sold in the US, and only
 for a minority or part categories.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: KBB-Cost-Regression"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 I regress these repair costs on the patents of the supplier-part.
 In column (2) I pay particular attention to firms which supply multiple
 products to the same model, and ask how those products differ in repair
 cost as a function of how innovative the supplier is in either product
 category.
 These estimates suggest a scaling parameter of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=10.63$
\end_inset

, corroborating the interpretation of patent variation as reflecting cost-reduci
ng innovations relevant to downstream buyers.
 
