\begin_layout Standard
First, I discuss the most straightforward effect, the effect of an increase
 in R&D on input demand: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{R\&D}_{f}}=\theta\rho=0.158.
\]

\end_inset

This is an elasticity for which many comparable estimates exist.
 A common reference, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bloom.etal2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, reports an elasticity of 0.041, derived from Compustat data across a broad
 set of industries.
 More broadly, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Leicester2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 summarizes a mean elasticity across studies of 0.095.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using the distribution of estimates they report in Figure 1, our estimate
 is roughly in the 70th percentile of estimates elasticities.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One interpretation for my higher estimate is industry composition: the
 automotive supply chain features some of the largest firms by R&D expenditure.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXX QJE paper
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Turning to the first 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spillover
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, I consider the effect of R&D expenditure by nearby firms, which affects
 local R&D productivity, on input demand.
 The implied elasticity is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Local}\text{R\&D}_{f}}=\theta\frac{\varrho+\rho}{1+\varrho+\rho}\gamma\rho\omega=0.161.
\]

\end_inset

Comparing with the previous elasticity suggest that a meaningful share of
 the returns to R&D are not captured by the expending firm.
 Again, for a comparable estimate, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bloom.etal2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 reports an elasticity of sales with respect to the R&D expenditure of other
 technologically similar firms of 0.191.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The spillover estimate reported from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bloom.etal2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is an R&D spillover, unconstrained by geography, from technologically similar
 firms.
 They authors also jointly estimate the contribution of geographic spillovers
 (0.117) alongside their baseline technological similarly spillover (0.101).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We finally have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Local Patents}_{c}}=\theta\frac{\varrho+\rho}{1+\varrho+\rho}\omega
\]

\end_inset

Now we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Patents}}{d\log\text{R\&D}}\approx\gamma\rho\implies\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Local R\&D}}=\theta\frac{\varrho+\rho}{1+\varrho+\rho}\gamma\rho\omega
\]

\end_inset

Going forward, we will hence use 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{R\&D Productivity}_{c}}{d\log\text{Local R\&D}_{c}}\equiv\tilde{\omega}=\gamma\rho\omega
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model also delivers a feedback between quantities and demand through
 the endogeneity of the R&D expenditures - a force that will tend to amplify
 the equilibrium response of prices to shocks.
 Consider a change in output supplier to buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, all else equal, the implied demand response at buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Quantity}_{f,k}}=-\theta\left(\frac{-\varrho}{1+\varrho}\mathbb{1}_{j=k}+\frac{1}{1+\varrho}\frac{-\rho}{1+\rho+\varrho}\lambda_{k}\right)=0.074\mathbb{1}_{j=k}+0.022\lambda_{f,k}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f,k}$
\end_inset

 is the share of the supplier 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

's specialized R&D expenditure on buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{1}_{j=k}$
\end_inset

 is an indicator that takes a value of 1 if 
\begin_inset Formula $j=k$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 if we are considering the demand response at the shocked buyer).
 The first term reflects a direct effect: an increase in quantity from buyer
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 raises the margin returns to specialized R&D for buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The second effect reflects the net of two opposing channels: an expansion
 in generic R&D as the marginal returns to generic innovation rise and a
 substitution channel, where specialized R&D is directed towards the shocked
 buyer.
 The greater role 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 plays in the R&D expenditure of supplier 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, the stronger these effects become.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we have the effects of production cost on demand.
 In the model, the pass through of baseline production costs to demand is
 attenuated by endogenous R&D investments.
 The implied elasticities are 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{f,m}=\mu_{f,m}\underbrace{c_{f,m}\vphantom{\sum_{j}\frac{\rho\bar{\zeta}_{f}}{\varrho\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}}}}_{\text{Market Specific Cost}}\underbrace{\left(\varrho\bar{\zeta}_{f,j_{m}}\bar{q}_{f,j_{m}}\bar{c}_{f,j_{m}}\vphantom{\sum_{j}\frac{\rho\bar{\zeta}_{f}}{\varrho\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}}}\right)^{\frac{-\varrho}{1+\varrho}}}_{\text{Buyer Specific R\&D}}\underbrace{\left(\sum_{j}\frac{\rho\bar{\zeta}_{f}}{\varrho\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}}\left(\varrho\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}\bar{q}_{f,j}\bar{c}_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\varrho}}\right)^{\frac{-\rho}{1+\rho+\varrho}}}_{\text{Generic R\&D}}
\]

\end_inset

So we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+\frac{-\varrho}{1+\varrho}+\frac{1}{1+\varrho}\frac{-\rho}{1+\rho+\varrho}
\]

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+\frac{1}{1+\varrho}\left(\frac{-\varrho\left(1+\rho+\varrho\right)-\rho}{1+\rho+\varrho}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\frac{1}{1+\varrho}\left(\frac{\left(\rho+\varrho\right)\left(1+\varrho\right)}{1+\rho+\varrho}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\frac{\left(\rho+\varrho\right)}{1+\rho+\varrho}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{0.138}{1+1.148+1.148}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Production Wages}_{f,j}}=-\theta\frac{\vartheta_{w}}{1+\rho+\varrho}=\underbrace{-0.077}_{=-\theta\times0.56}\text{ and }\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Traded Distance}_{f,j}}=-\theta\frac{\vartheta_{d}}{1+\rho+\varrho}=\underbrace{-0.074}_{=-\theta\times0.54}
\]

\end_inset

A useful benchmark for these estimates comes from the structural gravity
 literature.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Head.Mayer2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 report a median elasticity of 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\text{Trade}/d\log\text{Distance}=-1.14$
\end_inset

, and an estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\text{Trade}/d\log\text{Price}=-4.78$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Estimates come from Table 4, Distance row and median structural gravity
 column, and Table 5, structural gravity estimate row and median column.
 We take the estimate elasticity for nominal trade flows 
\begin_inset Formula $-3.78$
\end_inset

, and to interpret in terms of quantity assuming the standard trade elasticity
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-\sigma\right),$
\end_inset

we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=4.78$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Combining these estimate together, assuming full pass through of costs
 into prices, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\text{Cost}/d\log\text{Distance}=0.238$
\end_inset

, roughly half the size of our cost elasticity of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.54$
\end_inset

.
 One explanation for the difference is the lack of distance controls in
 our setting, biasing the estimate upwards.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Head.Mayer2013a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 refer to this endogeneity problem in estimating the effect of distance
 on trade as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dark matter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - where a positive correlation between distances and uncontrolled factors
 like regional trade agreements, languages, and preferences biases upwards
 the estimate.
 Since all distance parameters enter non-linearly into the GMM objective,
 controlling for a rich set of geographic factors is computationally infeasible.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As for the cost elasticity, many trade models assume a constant returns
 to scale production function in labor such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log Trade/d\log Wage=-\sigma$
\end_inset

, which would far exceed our estimated elasticity.
 But as for a direct estimate of production wages onto costs, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Head.Mayer2019a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 reports an elasticity of 0.63 in a sample of automotive OEMs - similar to
 our cost elasticity estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.56$
\end_inset

.
 But all in all, even if our cost-elasticities roughly match those found
 in prior work, the demand elasticities that follow differ sharply from
 prior work because of the low price elasticity of demand 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, I turn to the elasticities with respect to manufacturing proximity,
 which quantify the innovation losses associated with separating production
 from R&D.
 The implied elasticity of demand with respect to a supplier's own manufacturing
 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Manuf. Proximity}_{f,c}}=\frac{\theta\rho}{1+\rho+\varrho}\tau_{f}\lambda_{f,c}=\underbrace{0.095}_{=\theta\times0.68}\lambda_{f,c}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 represents the share of generic R&D expenditure done in location 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Manufacturing proximity matters primarily in the places where generic R&D
 happens.
 Increasing proximity in those locations raises R&D productivity, which
 lowers costs across buyers, increasing demand.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Buyer proximity will affect specialized R&D proximity and therefore has
 two channels.
 First, greater proximity to buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 increases the productivity of specialized R&D directed toward 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, lowering prices for that buyer.
 Second, because suppliers optimize across specialized and generic innovation,
 an increase in specialized productivity for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 induces substitution away from generic R&D which affects other buyers 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq k$
\end_inset

.
 The implied elasticity is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Buyer Proximity}_{f,k,c}}=\theta\frac{\varrho}{1+\varrho}\left(1-\frac{\rho}{1+\rho+\varrho}\lambda_{f,j,c}\right)\tau_{f,j}=\left(0.029\mathbb{1}_{j=k}-0.010\lambda_{f,k}\right)\lambda_{f,k,c}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f,k,c}$
\end_inset

 is the share of specialized R&D for buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 done in country 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{1}_{j=k}$
\end_inset

 is an indicator for if the shocked buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the same as the demanding buyer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And note that while 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma$
\end_inset

, which governs how substitutable R&D is across locations, does not directly
 enter any these elasticities, it governs how the R&D allocations (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f,j,c}$
\end_inset

) are determined as a function of location-specific productivity differences.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma$
\end_inset

, through the CES functional form, will also govern the love-of-variety
 effect from having more R&D locations active.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The large 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma$
\end_inset

, the more R&D tends to concentrate in the most productive location.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way to summarize the proximity, wage, and distance effects is through
 a compensating-variation thought exercise meant to represent the tradeoffs
 from offshoring.
 In particular, consider the wage savings required to offset the combined
 cost of greater trade distance and lower innovation productivity when productio
n is relocated abroad.
 Holding the rest of the environment fixed, the implied wage-distance frontier
 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{-\Delta\log\text{Wage}}{\Delta\log\text{Distance}}=\biggl(-\underbrace{\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Proximity}_{c}}}_{\text{Manuf. and/or Buyer Proximity}}+\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Traded}\text{Distance}_{f}}\biggr)/\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f,j}}{d\log\text{Production Wages}_{f}}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{f,m}=\mu_{f,m}\underbrace{c_{f,m}\vphantom{\sum_{j}\frac{\rho\bar{\zeta}_{f}}{\varrho\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}}}}_{\text{Market Specific Cost}}\underbrace{\left(\varrho\bar{\zeta}_{f,j_{m}}\bar{q}_{f,j_{m}}\bar{c}_{f,j_{m}}\vphantom{\sum_{j}\frac{\rho\bar{\zeta}_{f}}{\varrho\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}}}\right)^{\frac{-\varrho}{1+\varrho}}}_{\text{Buyer Specific R\&D}}\underbrace{\left(\sum_{j}\frac{\rho\bar{\zeta}_{f}}{\varrho\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}}\left(\varrho\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}\bar{q}_{f,j}\bar{c}_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\varrho}}\right)^{\frac{-\rho}{1+\rho+\varrho}}}_{\text{Generic R\&D}}
\]

\end_inset

and we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\left(\frac{c_{j,A}}{I_{j,A}^{\rho}}\right)^{\varrho}+\left(\sum_{p}\frac{c_{j,p}}{I_{j,p}^{\rho}}\right)^{\varrho}\right]^{\frac{1}{\varrho}}=\left(\rho\bar{q}_{j}\right)^{-\frac{\rho}{1+\rho}}\left(\left(\frac{\bar{c}_{j,A}}{\bar{\zeta}_{j,p}^{\rho}}\right)^{\frac{\varrho}{1+\rho\varrho}}+...\right)^{\frac{1}{\varrho}\frac{1+\rho\varrho}{1+\rho}}
\]

\end_inset

So we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log p_{f,m}}{d\log d_{fj}}=\frac{\varrho}{1+\rho+\varrho}\tau_{f,j}
\]

\end_inset

Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\bar{\zeta}_{j,p}}{d\log d_{jf}}=\tau_{j,f}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\log p=\lambda_{p}\frac{d\log p_{f,m}}{d\log d_{fj}}-\rho\frac{d\log\bar{\zeta}_{j,p}}{d\log d_{jf}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\log p=\lambda_{p}\frac{\varrho}{1+\rho+\varrho}\tau_{f,j}-\rho\tau_{j,f}
\]

\end_inset

So we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\tau_{f,j}}{1+1.15*2}=0.118\text{ and }1.15\times0.29=0.33
\]

\end_inset

And we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{\bar{\zeta}_{j,p}\bar{c}_{j,p}^{\varrho}}{\bar{\zeta}_{j,p}\bar{c}_{j,p}^{\varrho}}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\rho\varrho}}
\]

\end_inset

So we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0.29+0.118
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

This object stylistically represent the core tradeoffs from offshoring.
 Offshoring offers lowers factor prices, but increases trade costs and weakens
 innovation productivity by separating R&D from manufacturing.
 The frontier pins down exactly how large a wage differential must be to
 justify relocating production, where shutting down the proximity channel
 will highlight how much this new margin affects a firm's payoffs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: Offshoring-when-Buyer-Home"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 plots this threshold for suppliers initially producing, innovating, and
 selling in the US under different assumptions on the geography of R&D.
 First, the black line abstracts from innovation, and asks which locations
 offer lower unit costs determined solely by factor costs and distance.
 Introducing knowledge flows from manufacturing to innovation (blue line)
 shifts this threshold down - greater wage savings are needed to compensate
 for generic R&D productivity losses.
 Allowing the suppliers to also offshore R&D as well (red line) attenuates
 some of these losses, but not completely as buyers remain in the US and
 offshored R&D would make the specialized R&D component less productive.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When we introduce R&D spillovers from the location of manufacturing, the
 set of countries which are profitable to export to lower to those below
 the blue line.
 And, if suppliers offshoring R&D and manufacturing, the set of profitable
 locations are those below the red line.
 Note, suppliers in this final cast trade off the benefits of being close
 to their own manufacturing relative to proximity to buyers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
That is, for countries below the blue line, a firm in the US would find
 the cost savings sufficiently large to compensate the reduced R&D productivity
 and cost of shipment back to the US.
 Now, if firms were additionally willing to offshore their R&D, then this
 would raise the set of profitable locations to the regions below the red
 line.
 Here, note that offshored R&D keeps firms from experiencing the drop in
 generic R&D productivity, but comes at the cost of lower specialized R&D
 productivity since buyers remain in the US.
 And finally, if firms were unconcerned with R&D and simply cared about
 direct cost savings, then any region below the green line would yield lower
 prices.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: Offshoring-when-Buyer-Abroad"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 considers a different experiment where buyers are already assumed to be
 in the foreign country and suppliers are considering following.
 In the case with no innovation (black line), the threshold slopes up as
 suppliers are willing to tolerate higher wages as they benefit from decreased
 trade costs.
 Introducing knowledge flows from manufacturing to innovation (blue line)
 shifts this threshold down - decreased proximity lowers R&D productivity
 so much that unit costs will rise unless wages fall.
 And finally, if suppliers follow with their production and R&D (reg line),
 they would be willing to tolerate even higher wage increases than the no
 innovation case because they not only preserve the proximity to their own
 manufacturing, but also become closer to their buyers which raises specialized
 R&D productivity.
 All in all, this exercise highlights how when production is organized in
 global value chains, offshoring incentives for production and R&D depend
 on the joint location choices of upstream and downstream firms.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Next, we consider a different exercise, where we assume that buyers are
 already offshored.
 And we consider the threshold at which their suppliers are also willing
 to themselves offshore.
 Here we assume the firm in question is a supplier in China, and its buyers
 are already at the potential location being offshored to.
 We start again with the blue line, these are the locations a firm is willing
 to offshore just its production to.
 Now, the red line determines the regions that a firm would be willing to
 offshore production and innovation too.
 Note, firms would be willing to accept considerably higher production wages
 at a location in order to be closer to their buyers, since the increase
 in specialized R&D productivity and decrease in delivery distance would
 more than compensate the factor price increase.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{-\Delta\log\text{Wage}}{\Delta\log\text{Distance}}=\biggl(\underbrace{\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Downstream Proximity}_{c}}}_{\text{\ensuremath{\uparrow} Specialized R\&D Productivity}}+\underbrace{\frac{d\log\text{Demand}}{d\log\text{Distance}}}_{\text{\ensuremath{\downarrow} Trade Costs}}\biggr)/\underbrace{\frac{d\log\text{Demand}}{d\log\text{Wage}}}_{\text{Wage Savings}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

