.
 Although OEMs exhibit lower productivity returns to R&D (
\begin_inset Formula $\eta<\rho$
\end_inset

), they operate in substantially more elastic markets (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>\theta$
\end_inset

).
 Hence, the overall output response to innovation is similar in magnitude
 across the two stages of the supply chain.
 Why might OEMs be worse at generating productivity improvements? OEMs increasin
gly play the role of systems integrators, where their value is in having
 a platform that can combine the inputs across suppliers.
 Whereas suppliers innovate directly on the inputs used in production, OEMs
 innovate on the integration of those inputs into a product for downstream
 consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Turning to the demand elasticity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, I can compare to a large literature on estimating demand for the automobile
 industry.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Head.etal2026"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a recent summary of estimated elasticities.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1.241$
\end_inset

 is somewhat below the typical demand elasticity.
 But unlike the prior literature, identification here relies on variation
 from model-implied prices driven by innovation and a parsimonious set of
 cost shifters.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I refer to the data environment as parsimonious because the non-linear structure
 limits how many parameters we can estimate on, for example, the cost structure
 in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Supplier R&D Level and Prices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 By contrast, linear models like that in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Head.Mayer2019a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, a popular reference for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, allow for a richer set of controls and hence better measurement of cost.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Measurement error in costs or in the mapping from patents to effective
 cost reductions would attenuate the implied demand elasticity.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
While my estimate is lower than the typical point estimate, I am using a
 novel source of variation to predict demand shares by relying on differences
 in innovation to predict price difference.
 Prices will vary for additional un-modeled reasons that are (ideally) orthogona
l to innovation like vehicle characteristics and brand perception.
 The potential measurement error over 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

 will tend to attenuate estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
So, OEMs and Supplier seem just as capable of generating market-moving innovatio
n as one another.
 But, these demand elasticity they face are notable different.
 Suppliers seems more capable of creating cost-reducing innovations, but
 face lower demand elasticity.
 Next, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 smaller than what others estimate.
 Note, we do not use price data which variabilty from many other facts like
 markups, vehcile characteristics, etc.
 We use only one price by firm-market which is determined precisely by wage
 differencs, cost diffefents, and innovation differences.
 Our model does not capture many dimensions of firm heteogeneity, and the
 price differences predict likely explain less variation than the true price
 data captures.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relative importance of cost savings and innovation spillovers becomes
 clear when comparing wage and proximity elasticity.
 Consider first the effect of an increase in assembly wages on output.
 Because wages enter the marginal cost for assembly directly, the mode implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Output}_{j}}{d\log\text{Assembly Wages}_{j}}=-\sigma\frac{\vartheta_{w}}{1+\eta}\lambda_{j,A}=-1.04
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j,A}$
\end_inset

 is the share of assembly in the cost of the OEM (evaluated at the quantity-weig
hed average estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j,A}=0.50$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The share of inputs in final costs is something we have some empirical guidance
 over.
 In 2011, industry analysts estimated that the average global car's components
 cost $14,350.
 At the same time, average new vehicle prices were $25,048.
 Suggesting that 57% of a car's cost was in components - in-line with our
 estimated share.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://www.ft.com/content/ebb13af2-b4f5-390d-bc85-205905850d98#
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://www.energy.gov/cmei/vehicles/fact-744-september-10-2012-average-new-light-
vehicle-price-grows-faster-average-used
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 1% increase in assembly wages reduces output by roughly 1%.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By contrast, proximity affects output only through R&D productivity.
 The implied elasticity of output with respect to the OEMs own manufacturing
 (assembly plants) is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Output}_{j}}{d\log\text{Manuf. Proximity}_{j}}=-\sigma\frac{\eta}{1+\eta}\tau_{j}\lambda_{j,A}\lambda_{j,A,c}=0.086\lambda_{j,A,c}
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j,A,c}$
\end_inset

 is the share of assembly R&D expenditure done in country 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 OEM output is an order of magnitude more sensitive to production wages
 than to innovation effects from manufacturing proximity.
 This contrasts with the supplier's side, where wage and proximity elasticities
 were similar in magnitude.
 This asymmetry is driven primarily by the higher demand elasticity in final
 goods market: marginal cost changes translate into large quantity responses,
 while proximity effects operate through a smaller R&D return parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

.
 These magnitudes have direct implications for offshoring incentives.
 Facing weak innovation-based incentives to keep manufacturing and R&D co-locate
d, an OEM is willing to offshore manufacturing as the cost savings dwarf
 any losses from R&D productivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Joint offshoring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I now consider how offshoring decisions interact across the supply chain.
 The key distinction to focus on is unilateral relocation - where the OEM
 alone moves abroad and imports intermediates from home - and coordinate
 relocation - where suppliers and OEMs move together.
 Absent R&D interactions with manufacturing proximity, coordinated offers
 greater cost savings as both firms benefit from lower factor prices and
 inputs need not be traded across countries.
 But in the presence of proximity effects, both the absolute gains from
 offshoring and the relative gains from coordinate offshoring will be reduced.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fix ideas, I start by focusing on only production and trade costs.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Assembly Wages}_{j}}+\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Input Wages}_{f}}= & -\sigma\frac{\vartheta_{w}}{1+\eta}\left(\lambda_{j,A}+\frac{1}{1+2\rho}\left(1-\lambda_{j,A}\right)\right)=-1.043-0.307.\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{\text{Assembly Wages}}_{j}}-\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Input Trade Distance}_{f}}=-\sigma\frac{1}{1+\eta}\left(\vartheta_{w}\lambda_{j,A}-\frac{\vartheta_{d}}{1+2\rho}\left(1-\lambda_{j,A}\right)\right)=-1.043+0.297.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

When OEMs and suppliers jointly offshore they both experience wage savings.
 The direct effect on OEM output through assembly costs is 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\text{Demand}_{j}/d\log\text{Input Wages}_{f}=-1.04$
\end_inset

, and the indirect effect from wage savings at suppliers is 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\text{Demand}_{j}$
\end_inset

/
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\text{Input Wages}_{f}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $=-0.307$
\end_inset

.
 Despite the fact that assembly and inputs make up the same fraction of
 total costs, the output-cost elasticity is lower for input costs since
 suppliers are more productive at R&D 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho>\eta)$
\end_inset

, allowing them to compensate cost increases with R&D spending.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Formally, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\text{Cost}/\log\text{Input Cost}\times d\log\text{Input Cost}/\log\text{Input Wages}=-\sigma\frac{1}{1+\eta}\left(1-\lambda_{j,A}\right)\times\frac{\rho}{1+2\rho}\vartheta_{c}$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\left(1+2\rho\right)$
\end_inset

 captures the fact that an increase in input costs raises the incentive
 to do R&D and this reduces the passthrough of input costs to OEM costs.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the case where there is unilateral offshoring by OEMs, the savings in
 assembly wages are offset by an increase in trade costs for intermediates:
 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\text{Demand}_{j}/d\log\text{Input Trade Distance}_{f}=-0.297.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unilateral versus coordinated offshoring comparison, under the case
 of no manufacturing proximity effects on R&D, is governed by a clear wage-dista
nce tradeoff visualized in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: USA-Offshoring-w/-No-Innovation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 From the perspective of a supply chain initially in the US - lower unit
 costs would be realized under unilateral offshoring to any location under
 the blue line.
 Coordinated offshoring expands the set of locations that would lower unit
 costs to those under the red line.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introducing manufacturing proximity effects in R&D adds additional productivity
 costs from offshoring - beyond those observed within an OEM.
 At, offshoring OEM production away from suppliers reduces the productivity
 of specialized R&D; and thereafter, offshoring supplier production reduces
 the productivity of generic R&D.
 Quantitatively, these effects have the following magnitude: 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Buyer Proximity}_{f,j,c}}=\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Input Cost}_{f,j}}\times\frac{d\log\text{Input Cost}_{j}}{d\log\text{Buyer Proximity}_{f,j,c}}=-\sigma\frac{1}{1+\eta}\lambda_{j,f}\times\frac{\rho}{1+2\rho}\tau_{f,j}\left(\lambda_{f,j,c}\right)=0.075\lambda_{f,j,c}.
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Manuf. Proximity}_{f,j,c}}=\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Input Cost}_{f,j}}\times\frac{d\log\text{Input Cost}_{j}}{d\log\text{Buyer Proximity}_{f,j,c}}=-\sigma\frac{1}{1+\eta}\lambda_{j,f}\times\frac{\rho}{1+2\rho}\tau_{f}\left(\lambda_{f,c}\right)=0.376\lambda_{f,j,c}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Buyer Proximity}_{f,j,c}}=0.075\lambda_{f,j,c}\text{ and }\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Manuf. Proximity}_{f,j,c}}=0.376\lambda_{f,c}.
\]

\end_inset

While these are meaningful, they remain small relative to wage-driven cost
 effects.
 Innovation spillovers therefore dampen, but do not overturn, an OEMs strong
 cost-based incentive to offshore.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For the similarities to the supplier estimates, note that the effect of
 manufacturing proximity is comparable: 
\begin_inset Formula $.086$
\end_inset

 (OEMs) versus .095 (suppliers).
 As for the differences, the elasticity of output with respect to wages
 is 15 time larger for OEMs relative to suppliers - a difference mostly
 driven by demand elasticities 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 This means that faced with an opportunity to offshore, which reduces production
 costs at the expense of R&D productivity, an OEM will be more likely to
 capitulate relative to a supplier.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Now, we can consider how the joint offshoring choices of OEMs and supplier
 may interact.
 First, note that in a model without R&D spillovers, the offshoring payoff
 depends on if suppliers follow-suit.
 If suppliers remain at Home, then buyers will have to pay higher import
 costs for inputs, but if suppliers follow in offshoring then OEMs will
 experience lower inputs costs as their suppliers wages also fall:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Assembly Wages}_{j}}+\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Input Wages}_{f}}= & -\sigma\frac{\vartheta_{w}}{1+\eta}\left(\lambda_{j,A}+\frac{1}{1+2\rho}\left(1-\lambda_{j,A}\right)\right)=-1.043-0.307.\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset

Liekwise,....
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{\text{Assembly Wages}}_{j}}-\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{j}}{d\log\text{Input Trade Distance}_{f}}=-\sigma\frac{1}{1+\eta}\left(\vartheta_{w}\lambda_{j,A}-\frac{\vartheta_{d}}{1+2\rho}\left(1-\lambda_{j,A}\right)\right)=-1.043+0.297.
\]

\end_inset

We represent the difference in payoffs from unilateral versus coordinate
 offshoring in Figure 10, where again firms are trading off the factor cost
 savings form the cost of exporting back to H.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When we reintroduce manufacturing spillovers onto R&D, the picture changes.
 First, the unlitareal offshoring descion poses a negative R&D effect into
 not just buyers, but also their supplers: So if OEMs move abroad they impose
 a negative R&D effect on suppliers.
 Now to reduces costs they naturally may want their suppliers to offshore
 as well.
 But that poses an even larger R&D externality onto suppliers as they are
 now further from their own manufacturing.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: USA-Offshoring-w/-Innovation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
