\begin_layout Subsection
Non-Linear Effects - R&D Reallocation, Spillovers, and Equilibrium Adjustments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now interpret how offshoring affects outcomes through R&D productivity
 by asking how much firms need to be compensated for R&D losses associated
 with the separation of manufacturing from R&D.
 We can imagine policies that compensate firms in a number of ways.
 First, I consider compensating firms using a sales subsidy (% of sale value)
 or compensating their production wages ($ per hourly worker wage).
 Compensating production wages is effectively what offshoring offers firms.
 But since OEMs and suppliers are variably affected by changes in input
 costs, I additionally consider output subsidies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I will additionally consider compensation under two scenarios.
 The baseline scenario assumes all R&D is done at Home.
 The multinational R&D scenario assumes that the firm moves part of their
 R&D abroad.
 Where I impose that firms split their R&D expenditure across both Home
 and the offshoring destination in proportion to the shares observed in
 the data.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Wage Compensation}=\text{\text{Production Wage}_{f}}\times\left[\exp\left(\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f}}{d\log\text{Proximity}_{f,c}}/\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f}}{d\log\text{Production Wage}_{f}}\Delta\log\text{Proximity}_{f,c}\left(\lambda_{f,c}-\lambda_{f,c'}\right)^{\mathbb{1}\left\{ \text{Multinational R\&D}\right\} }\right)-1\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

So for example, the output subsidy requires to compensate the R&D losses
 from offshoring is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Subsidy}\%\approx100\times\frac{d\log\text{Demand}_{f}}{d\log\text{X Proximity}_{f,c}}\Delta\log\text{Proximity}_{f,c}\left(\lambda_{f,H}-\lambda_{f,c'}\right)^{\mathbb{1}\left\{ \text{Multinational R\&D}\right\} }
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f,c}$
\end_inset

