First, we ask how does the level of patents change in response to an increase
 of production proximity in one location: 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{ and }\frac{d\log\text{\ensuremath{\frac{\text{Specialized Patents}_{j,c}}{\sum_{c}\text{Specialized Patents}_{j,c}}}}}{d\log\text{Down Proximity}_{j,c}}=\tau_{f,j}\left(1+\frac{\zeta}{1-\zeta}\right)=1.91.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{\sum_{c}\text{Generic Patents}_{f,c}}}{d\log\text{Upstream Proximity}_{f,c}}=\tau_{f}\frac{1+\varrho}{1+\rho+\varrho}\rho\gamma\lambda_{f,c}=1.64\lambda_{f,c}\text{ where }\lambda_{f,c}=\frac{\left[\zeta_{f,c}r_{c}^{-\zeta}\right]^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}}{\sum_{c}\left[\zeta_{f,c}r_{c}^{-\zeta}\right]^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}}.
\]

\end_inset

Consider a single-location firm, a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

% increase in the proximity of a firm to its own manufacturing facilities
 raises patents by 
\begin_inset Formula $1.64\times\lambda_{f,c}$
\end_inset

% where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f,c}$
\end_inset

 is the share of location 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 in the R&D spending of firm 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, firm increasingly concentrate their R&D spending in the location which
 yields the highest R&D productivity next of cost.S o despite the fact that
 firms are multinationals in their innovation strategies - the total level
 of innovation is determined largely by their most productive location.
 This reflects a lot of prior work that has highlighted the unique role
 of HQ services.
 This matches things like XXX.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, then R&D outcome increasingly become determined by the most productive
 R&D location - matches Bilir & Morales.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To get a sense of the role of across-location substitution in determining
 R&D outcomes, consider some 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f,c}\approx0$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{\text{Generic Patents}_{f,k}/\sum_{c}\text{Generic Patents}_{f,c}}}{d\log\text{Upstream Proximity}_{f,k}}=\tau_{f}\Bigl(1+\underbrace{\frac{\zeta}{1-\zeta}}_{=2.28}\Bigr)=1.23
\]

\end_inset

where the majority of the elasticity is driven by a substitution effect
 rather than a direct productivity effect.
 Another key geographic factor is local knowledge spillovers, the estimates
 suggest the following elasticity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\text{\sum_{c}\text{Generic Patents}_{f,c}}}{d\log\text{Local Patents}_{f,c}}=\omega\frac{1}{1+\rho+\varrho}\rho\gamma\lambda_{c}=0.17\lambda_{f,c},
\]

\end_inset

so a 1% increase in the level of local patenting in some country 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 raises a firms patents by 
\begin_inset Formula $0.17\times\lambda_{f,c}$
\end_inset

%.
 
\end_layout

